Shouldn't this be an `abbrev` instead, so that one can call it `.\eps_` outside of the `Ordinal` namespace?

I don't want to make `epsilon` a separate definition, since then it would necessitate writing API theorems for linking it back to `veblen`, such as `epsilon (veblen a) = veblen a` when `1 < a` (this is a consequence of `veblen_veblen_of_lt`). Conversely, I don't really see the issue with just calling `veblen 1` by `epsilon` in theorem names.

> I don't want to make `epsilon` a separate definition, since then it would necessitate writing API theorems for linking it back to `veblen`

Not if it's an `abbrev`
Not much seems to break if I take your advice, so alright then!
eg `abbrev epsilon := ...` would justify the name here

```suggestion
theorem natCast_lt_epsilon (n : â„•) (o : Ordinal) : n < Îµ_ o :=
```

```suggestion
theorem natCast_lt_gamma (n : â„•) : n < Î“_ o :=
```
Isn't `Order` open here already? If not, maybe it should
Can `simp` see through `abbrev`? If so, this should just be a specific case of `veblen_pos`.
